26 2021-01-03 feeling hot his gums became discolored and turned purple/gums (both sides up and down) remain purple/discolorati... Read more
Close
his gums became discolored and turned purple/gums (both sides up and down) remain purple/discoloration to the gums in his mouth; his mouth started hurting; feeling hot; Body aches; Fever; Pain to the gums in his mouth; muscle aches; sore throat; neck pain; This is a spontaneous report from a contactable nurse (patient). A 26-year-old male patient received the first dose of bnt162b2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 VACCINE, solution for injection, lot number and expiration date were not reported), via an unspecified route of administration to right shoulder on 24Dec2020 11:30 at a single dose for COVID-19 immunization. There were no medical history and concomitant medications. The patient received vaccine on 24Dec2020. He experienced body aches, fever, and feeling hot with onset of about 3-4 hours after he was administered (24Dec2020). Next day (25Dec2020), his mouth started hurting, his gums became discolored and turned purple. Gums (both sides up and down) remained purple. He will be seeing a dentist. He also reported pain and discoloration to the gums in his mouth on 25Dec2020. He had been experiencing some of the regular side effects such as muscle aches, sore throat, neck pain on an unspecified date in Dec2020. Outcome of the event gum discoloration was not recovered, of the events feeling hot, generelized aching, and fever was recovered on 26Dec2020, of the event gum pain was recovering, and of the remaining events was unknown. He reported seriousness criteria as what he thinks to be medically significant at this point; that they could be medically significant. He is scheduled to receive the second dose of the product which at this point he does not plan to change. Dose change is unknown until he determines cause of these events and on what the doctor and dentist he is going to see recommend. He believes events could be caused by the vaccine. Information on the lot/batch number has been requested.; Sender's Comments: A causal association between BNT162 and the reported events cannot be excluded based on a compatible temporal relation. The impact of this report on the benefit/risk profile of the Pfizer product is evaluated as part of Pfizer procedures for safety evaluation, including the review and analysis of aggregate data for adverse events. Any safety concern identified as part of this review, as well as any appropriate action in response, will be promptly notified to RAs, Ethics Committees, and Investigators, as appropriate.

26 2021-02-10 unresponsive to stimuli Patient presented with puffy eyes approximately 4 minutes after vaccination. Was alert and oriented ... Read more
Close
Patient presented with puffy eyes approximately 4 minutes after vaccination. Was alert and oriented to time, person, and place upon questioning and was able to engage in conversation. Parent (mother) of patient was present who gave patient's medical history and reported allergy to grass with similar reaction. Blood pressure was taken and found to be 150/80. Mother reported patient had not taken his blood pressure medicine yet that day but his normal is 115/70 with medication. While nurse was assessing patient's pulse (patient's pulse was WNL at 85) and other nursing staff was obtaining medication to administer if needed after assessment, patient became unresponsive to verbal commands and his upper body became limp. At 1054, a one time, single dose of 50 mg of diphenhydramine IM was given in the left deltoid. On site EMT arrived on the scene at 1055, completed assessment, and confirmed giving diphenhydramine was the best course of action. At this time, 1055, patient became responsive to verbal commands and was oriented to time, place, and person. At 1056 O2 sat was at 97%, pulse 70, and at 1100, BP was 110/70. Patient stayed for observation 30 more minutes and remained stable. Patient and parent were educated on side effects of diphenhydramine, to watch for any returning symptoms of allergic reaction throughout the day, and if/when to head to the ER. Recommended patient not receive 2nd dose of COVID vaccination.

I know that operating a motor vehicle will not be possible for me.

I took notes during my wait time: -6 minutes in my throat felt weird, but different than normal allergic reactions to foods. I prepared my Epi-Pen so I have easier access at this time. -9 minutes in the sides of my tongue were slightly itchy. -11 minutes in and I felt as though the saliva in the back of my throat was thicker and I needed to clear my throat a bit more often, similar to allergic reactions. -15 minutes in, I felt my heart pound once out of beat, but my heart rhythm returned to normal immediately. Tongue itchiness also became intermittent rather than constant. -18 minutes in, overall condition improved and I felt better. -22 minutes in, my throat felt scratchy like I would if I consumed legumes (chickpeas, green peas, soy beans, etc.) but also oddly warm, which was out of the norm. No treatments needed given mild reactions. I went to work, but notified my co-workers of my reaction, so if my condition worsens they can help administer my Epi-Pen. I am reporting this at 9:21 am on 03/05/2021, roughly an hour after my first dose.

26 2021-05-25 weakness A 26-year-old male with no past medical history presents to the emergency department (ED) with an ac... Read more
Close
A 26-year-old male with no past medical history presents to the emergency department (ED) with an acute episode of chest pain. He reports initially mild dull substernal chest pain for a day prior to an episode of acute sharp chest pain that radiates to his left neck and left shoulder accompanied by diaphoresis leading him to present to the ED. He had received the second dose of the Pfizer-BioNTech mRNA COVID-19 vaccine three days prior to presentation and reported myalgia and weakness beginning within 24 hours of vaccination. His blood pressure on arrival was 126/83 mmHg and pulse was 61 bpm. Electrocardiogram (ECG) on admission showed diffuse upsloping 2mm STE, no reciprocal changes, and PR elevation in aVR. Troponin-I on admission was 6.03 ng/ml prior to peaking at 21 ng/ml while initial CRP was 56.8 mg/L. Transthoracic echo (TTE) showed left ventricular ejection fraction (LVEF) of 55-60% with hypokinesis of the basal lateral wall. Cardiac magnetic resonance imaging (CMR) was consistent with myocarditis showing subepicardial late gadolinium enhancement (LGE) in the basal inferior wall, no edema on T2 sequences, and a mildly reduced left ventricular systolic function with an LVEF of 51%. He was started on colchicine, low dose beta blocker and losartan and improved symptomatically along with resolution of the EKG findings prior to being discharged with plan for close outpatient follow-up and repeat imaging. In addition, a respiratory viral PCR panel was obtained which was positive for Rhinovirus/Enterovirus on nasal swab. Although it is possible that his presentation was secondary to enteroviral myocarditis, the temporal relationship to the second dose of Pfizer-BioNTech mRNA COVID-19 vaccine suggests the possibility of myocarditis secondary to immunologic response to COVID-19 vaccine itself.

Within 30 seconds of that, he knew he needed help, so alerted the emergency medical technicians (EMTs) via car horn/flashers. Normally, he could tell 1-3 minutes in advance that he would black out. This time, it was about 30 seconds. He had no symptoms since a week after his initial exposure to coronavirus. No adverse reactions but turned up with infection. The outcome of event burning sensation on the face and upper torso was recovered on 01Jan2021, outcome of the other events was unknown. Reporter assessed seriousness for burning sensation on face and upper torso: Medically significant. Causality between burning sensation on face and upper torso and bnt162b2 was related by Primary Source Reporter per Global Introspection. Information on the batch number/lot number has been requested.; Sender's Comments: Based on the current available information , Exposure to SARS-CoV-2 is most likely related to an intercurrent condition which is not related to the suspected drug. Based on the plausible drug-event temporal association, a possible contributory role of the suspect product BNT162B2 to the development of other events cannot be totally excluded. The case will be reassessed if additional information becomes available. The impact of this report on the benefit/risk profile of the Pfizer product is evaluated as part of Pfizer procedures for safety evaluation, including the review and analysis of aggregate data for adverse events. Any safety concern identified as part of this review, as well as any appropriate action in response, will be promptly notified to Regulatory Authorities, Ethics Committees and Investigators, as appropriate.

After about an hour following my second COVID-19 Injection I began feeling warm. My forehead felt warmer so I figure I may have had a slight fever at that point. I received a metallic (Note I say metallic but I know it wasn't actually metal but that's simply the best way I can describe the taste I experienced) following the injection about 5 minutes after. My arm remained sore following and still remains sore as of this report. I experienced a decline in mental acuity following about an hour after injection. I began to feel lightheaded and exhausted to the point I was experiencing severe disorientation and confusion. I was having trouble putting sentences together and experienced a ringing sensation in the ears. I felt like I wasn't even present anymore. I couldn't comprehend things around me and apparently had conversations I don't even remember having. Note that at that point I had gotten home but don't even remember getting home. I just know that this did not begin to wear off until around 8:45pm when it was like someone flipped a switch and I suddenly was coherent again. It was an odd sensation to experience. The arm remained sore and the metallic taste returned briefly after this experience. I experienced a similar feeling from the HPV injection years ago, but just like this it was a temporary thing that resulted in no long term issues. However, I cannot tell you fully what we did the rest of the day until around 845-9 pm. I also remember becoming partly agitated after the injection like my body just all of a sudden took notice of something and shot into action. I had received my allergy injections this same day about two hours earlier as well and none of these reactions ever occur with those for me. I continued to drink liquid as far as I know as there were a few empty bottles of water next to me. I have no recollection of getting them. It's odd. There's just this brief moment in time that is just missing from my memory with a few short bits and pieces that are there like a puzzle with some missing pieces. I feel I became so fatigued I could not function. My emotions I remember were off and hard to control during this period too. I felt like I was having some random mood swings. I feel ok now though aside from the upset stomach occasionally and the fatigue and arm pain (but even the arm pain has partly decreased now). It all ceased. I have a number of health issues outside of this but have not experienced this long of a period of almost intermittent amnesia and incoherency following an injection before. I believe it made me that much more tired or reacted with one of my many conditions or genetic variants that perhaps may have been part of this. I'm happy to provide anything I can to help with this. I am greatly appreciative of all the CDC has done to get us this vaccine and continues to do to ensure our safety both before and after injection. It is commendable. I did fill out my survey through the V-Safe portal as well and will continue to follow up there should I have any changes. I have not sought medical care following this event as the coherency and such have seemed to resolve in regards to the vaccine injection. Only thing left are known side effects at this point besides an occasional increase in numbness and tingling that I already experience in my legs and feet. My absolute best guess for the cause is my immune system which already has some issues regulating (doesn't always like to learn everything it should and we are currently searching for an undiagnosed autoimmune disorder currently going on as well in me) on top of allergy shots today. it was perhaps just a bit too much demand on it all at once. But it seems to be balancing out again now.

Upon receipt of follow-up information on 28Dec2020, this case now contains all required information to be considered valid. This is a spontaneous report from a contactable other healthcare professional (HCP). A 29-years-old male patient received bnt162b2 (lot number: EJ1685), intramuscular (deltoid left) on 21Dec2020 at 05:30 at 0.3 mL single (first dose) for Covid. Medical history was reported as "none". Concomitant medications were not reported. The patient previously received Flu vaccine in Oct2020 for immunization. The patient is an Occupational Therapist, and he called to report an adverse event that he experienced with the first dose of the COVID Vaccine. He received the vaccine last Monday, 21Dec2020 at 5:30AM before his shift at work, then 20 minutes later, he was having severe stroke like symptoms. He experienced severe left sided weakness, loss of balance, extreme numbness and tingling in his left hand and foot, he had issues finding his words and he couldn't speak, and he had an oral motor impairment where his mouth was weak and not coordinated. The staff at the hospital did a neurological exam on him, and he failed, so he had to go to the emergency room (ER). The patient added that he was already in the hospital when this happened, and the ER doctors suspected that he had a CVA, and they gave him TPA to prevent any permanent brain damage and it worked. The patient then added that due to the shock of this whole event, from everything that happened, it has weakened his heart. Reportedly, he is a healthy 29 year old man, with no preexisting conditions, and he works out, and he has no heart conditions, but he had to get a cardiology follow up a few days after he got the vaccine, because he started going in to Ventricular Tachycardia, which he had never had in his life. So, the doctors at the hospital went ahead and did an Echocardiogram and an EKG, and he was told that his Ejection Fraction is down to 25%. He stated his heart is so weak, that he cannot work right now, but the structure of his heart is fine and has not had any damage. The hospital staff thought that maybe the patient had a chronic heart issue that he just did not know about, and that the stress of this event maybe made it kick into overdrive, but he states that the cardiologist said that was not the case, because the structure of his heart is fine, and the only thing they can see is that the heart is pumping weak. One physician even suggested that due to the shock of the event, he might have Takotsubo Cardiomyopathy, which is a broken heart, but because the structure of his heart is okay, it should be reversible. He stated that he is hoping he will heal up good, because he is young and has no pre-existing conditions. He added that his heart is in such a state right now; he has to wear an external defibrillator. The patient stated that all these happened about 20 minutes after he received the vaccine, and he was admitted to the hospital from 21Dec2020 to 25Dec2020. His neurological symptoms have resolved except that he has a stutter that he did not have before and his mouth is fatigued easily, so he has to slow down when he is eating, but now he can eat regular for the most part. The patient confirmed that he was not specifically prescribed the product; it was administered to him at his place of work, but it was optional. He stated he considered how he is working with COVID patients every day, and given the circumstance, he thought that it would be a best practice for him to get the vaccine. He had not gone to his primary care doctor in a while because he had been fine and healthy, but he called them and found out that his primary care had retired, so he has to find a new one now. Regarding the issues finding words and trouble speaking, he stated that he has improved, but it is still ongoing, he is just stuck in a plateau zone. With the Ventricular Tachycardia, he stated that this is an ongoing issue, as he has to wear the life vest even though he has no need to activate it yet. He did have one minor bought of the VTach, but because he is a therapist, he knows how to take care of it with relaxation techniques, he knows how to manage it. He had one bought of VTach the evening prior, but he was able to get it under control. The doctors have him on medication to help keep his heart rate at bay. He has never had to use medication before and is on the following medications to help keep his heart rate at bay: Metoprolol 25mg one tablet once daily by mouth and Lisinopril 5mg one tablet once daily by mouth. The VTach has improved, it was good enough he was able to discharge home, but it is still a concern. His cardiologist said that, basically his hope, is that once his body recover from the whole shock of everything, then his ejection fraction will heal, and his heart will heal. He again stated that the doctor told him that the structure of his heart is perfectly fine; he has thick walls in his heart, no leaking valves, and the heart was not conducting any abnormal signals. The doctor just said that right now, his heart is super weak and that it is an acute problem. With the Takotsubo Cardiomyopathy, he states that two doctors mentioned this diagnosis, but he confirmed that he was not actually diagnosed with this issue, he was just diagnosed with Ventricular Tachycardia. The outcome of the ejection fraction down to 25% was unknown to the patient at this time as he has not had another EKG or echocardiogram, but the cardiologist told him that the cardiologist expects that this will not be resolved quickly anyway. The patient confirmed that he did not receive any other vaccines on the same day he received the COVID vaccine. The only other vaccine he had this year was the flu vaccine which he got back in Oct2020. He has gone on to his online portal and there are the bloodwork results and all the imaging results on there from his CTs and MRIs, but he did not see the EKG or Echocardiogram results yet. He does not have this pulled up at this time, but he does have access to this stuff and can provide it later, if requested. He is curious about the next steps from here to how his case is processed. He is also curious if this information would help Pfizer make modifications to the vaccine if it is found that a lot of people are having the same reaction as he did. He is also wondering, given his situation, that probably he is not going to get the second dose, for his safety, but he is wondering what percentage of effectiveness the first dose does having just covered. The events left sided weakness, loss of balance, extreme numbness and tingling in left hand and foot resolved on 25Dec2020; severe stroke like symptoms and oral motor impairment; mouth weakness and not coordinated/mouth is fatigued easily resolved in 2020. The events ventricular tachycardia/help keep his heart rate at bay and issues finding words and trouble speaking were resolving, stutter had not resolved while the outcome of the events it has weakened his heart, and ejection fraction down to 25% was unknown.; Sender's Comments: The reported information is unclear and does not allowa meaningful assessment of the case. After receiving the vaccine, I was instructed to wait i for 15 minutes to ensure there were no reactions. I sat down in the provided chair, put my headphones in my ears, and started my timer on my watch for 15 minutes. after about 5 minutes I began to feel like my injection arm was a little weak, as if perhaps my arm was stiffening from the injection sore. I remember feeling slightly warm and started to read over the COVID-19 Vaccine symptoms sheet and then I blacked out (Fainted). The nurse in the hallway woke me up and was asking me if i was alright and then rushed me in the back room where they tested me and ensured I was ok. I had not eaten anything the morning of the vaccination shot and barely anything the night before. I have been experiencing higher levels of anxiety recently due to pressures of day to day life; school, work, etc. The nurses are thinking it is likely I had more of a reaction to the anxiety and low food or blood sugar (I am not diabetic), than a reaction to the vaccine itself. They did refer to my experience as sounding like Vasovagal syncope. I have never had this experience with any flu vaccine or shots before; I do not have a fear of needles or shots.

A 31-year-old male patient received the first dose of BNT162B2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 VACCINE, lot number: EN6201) via an unspecified route of administration in left arm on 21Feb2021 11:30 a.m. at age of 31-year-old, at single dose for COVID-19 immunisation. The patient had history of frequent ear infections. Concomitant medication included fluticasone which was taken within 2 weeks of vaccination for an unspecified indication. The patient did not receive any other vaccines within 4 weeks prior to the COVID vaccine. The patient was not diagnosed with COVID-19 prior to vaccination. The patient had not been tested for COVID-19 since the vaccination. The patient reported when he woke up the next day after receiving the vaccine (22Feb2021), he found that he was suffering from paralysis and numbness on the left side of his face. He went to the emergency room (ER) and was diagnosed with Bell's Palsy. He had been experiencing some minor pain in his left ear beginning two days before he received the vaccine (i.e., three days before onset of facial paralysis), and this ear pain had continued as he continue to experience the palsy. Since visiting the ER, he had also seen a neurologist. The doctors he had seen do not necessarily think that the palsy resulted from receiving the vaccine. The onset date of the event "I was suffering from paralysis and numbness on the left side of my face. I went to the ER and was diagnosed with bell's palsy" was reported as 22Feb2021 09:00 a.m. The event result in doctor or other healthcare professional office/clinic visit and emergency room/department or urgent care. The event was non-serious (the event did not result in death, not life threatening, not caused/prolonged hospitalization, no disabling/Incapacitating, no congenital anomaly/birth defect). Oral steroid and antiviral drugs, eye ointment was received to treat the event. The outcome of the event was not recovered. No follow-up attempts are possible. No further information is expected.

32 2021-05-26 discomfort, feeling hot, pain in extremity I received the COVID-19 vaccine at 9:30 am from vaccination clinic. I had just recovered from COVID-... Read more
Close
I received the COVID-19 vaccine at 9:30 am from vaccination clinic. I had just recovered from COVID-19 about two and a half weeks prior. I had no immediate reaction. I worked the entire day with no adverse effects other than a sore arm, which I expected. Later in the day at about 7:45 pm I went for a 6 mile run and got home at approximately 8:49 pm. Within half an hour of getting home, I quickly became feverish. The fever continued to rise until I was extremely hot, and hotter than I can ever remember as an adult or child. I did not have access to a thermometer so I cannot reliably report what the temperature was but I am estimating 103. It felt like every part of my body, including my legs, was hot to the touch. By 1 am I had serious chills and was shivering under winter blankets despite an outdoor temperature of 70-80. In addition, I had an extremely elevated heart rate and chest pain. I also had generalized muscle aches all over my body. I did not sleep at all that night. The fever began to slowly dissipate early in the morning but the elevated heart rate continued for approximately 24 hours. The discomfort resulting from my elevated heart rate was substantial and alarming enough that I sought advice from my primary care physician after a nurse at my Occupational Health clinic suggested potentially getting an ECG. Ultimately, by Thursday morning, the symptoms had decreased and I declined any follow up. However, this was the single worst reaction I've ever had to any vaccine and the single worst fever I've ever experienced as an adult or in my memory as a child. Although I am aware that people who have already had COVID-19 tend to have worse reactions to the first COVID vaccine, I am filing this report primarily because of my concern that exercise may trigger an especially severe reaction.

33 year old healthy man presented with seizure to Hospital ER on 5/7/2021. He required intubation. 33 2021-03-10 tingling I started having radicular tingling with neck flexion that ran down my left leg starting at the begi... Read more
Close
I started having radicular tingling with neck flexion that ran down my left leg starting at the beginning of February. I noted it to a colleague and asked if anyone else who had received the vaccine at the same time as me had any similar effects. I was the only person noted. Slowly the tingling increased and began radiating the entire length of the left leg. It only last for a few seconds at the beginning of flexion then completely resolved. I did not think much of this at the time and figured that it would resolve. On February 27, I began having visual disturbances and symptoms similar to vertigo with a severe nystagmus with a gaze the the right. I attempted a round of azithromycin at this time thinking that there may be an ear infection and that was causing my visual/vertigo like symptoms. There was no improvement with this course of treatment and the visual issues were becoming more of a regular issue. It became hard for me to focus anytime that I would look to my right but was able to focus my eyes while looking forward and the the left. At this time, I opted to have a brain MRI done which was completed on Match 9th as well as having basic labs run. I ended up with an elevated white count on my labs with a left shift. My MRI was read the same day showing a demyelinating process. Multiple neurologist were consulted on this and they believe that my symptoms are not related to MS as the radiologist listed as his top three on his differential but rather what they called post-covid vaccine syndrome, similar to what they are seeing with patients who actually had COVID. I have no medical history, I am not taking any medications and had no symptoms prior to the vaccine. My symptoms were acutely brought on unlike MS and I do not have any of the four most common male characteristics of MS. I do not currently have any muscle weakness, I am not fatigued, it has not progressed to my upper extremities, it does not have a stalking glove approach but rather shoots down, I have no sexual dysfunction. I have been started on a high dose prednisone taper as recommended by the neurologist. My biggest concern is that when I looked for information as a medical provider, I was unable to find anything related to neurological issues and the vaccine. Once, I was placed in contact with multiple neurologist, I was told that they are seen quite a few neurological adverse events.

Response: Spoke from EUA PI (Revised: 06 April 2021) under Post Authorization Experience Fact Sheet for Recipients and Caregivers (Revised: 06 April 2021) under section WHAT ARE THE RISKS OF THE PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 VACCINE? As noted in the Fact Sheet for Recipients, you should not get the Pfizer-BioNTech COVID-19 Vaccine if you had a severe allergic reaction after a previous dose of the vaccine or if you had a severe allergic reaction to any ingredient of the vaccine. The decision to receive the second dose for any other reason cannot be made by Pfizer. We refer you to speak to your healthcare provider about the risks of the vaccine compared to the risks of potentially not being fully protected against COVID-19 infection. Your healthcare provider knows your health situation and has access to information that can better help inform this decision. RN reports he'd had a vagal response, most likely due to witnessed severe anxiety during IM injection (name /right deltoid @ 10:23a). RN gave him Gatorade and he quickly became AOx3. When EMS arrived, he was able to stand up, with assist, and be placed on the gurney. EMS monitored him for ~ 20min onsite, at which time he became hypotensive, resulting in transport to the nearest ER with O2 and IV management. Per HR representative for a business patient was discharged @ ~2p the same day, with diagnosis of severe dehydration and hypokalemia, his reaction most likely a vagal event. Unknown if medications were given outpatient.

First dose of vaccine received on April 6. Soreness in arm for remainder of day, slight fever to 100.5 that night. No symptoms for remainder of week. Slight cough began in the morning on April 12, no other symptoms at that point. Woke up on April 13 with 101.4 F temperature, and throat soreness that made swallowing incredibly painful. Sore throat has made continuous sleep nearly impossible for the next two days (so far), as whenever I swallow I wake myself up, which happens every 10-15 minutes. This has resulted in general fatigue throughout the day. Fever, sore throat, coughing all get worse at night time. Average temperature during the day has been 99.5 F, while temperature readings after 10 PM have been in the 101-102 F range. Appears to be semi-breakthrough SARS-CoV-2 infection (i.e. after first dose of vaccine, but before second dose), based on timing of symptoms and subsequent positive PCR test.

34 2021-04-15 discomfort, tingling, seizure Within an hour of receiving the vaccine, I began to feel "odd" (i.e heart racing, spine tingling, st... Read more
Close
Within an hour of receiving the vaccine, I began to feel "odd" (i.e heart racing, spine tingling, strange sensations in my hands, and dizziness). At the hour mark, while trying to "walk it off" inside my backyard, things escalated quickly. As I came back inside, I suddenly collapsed and and lost consciousness. Luckily my best friend was with me and she described my behavior as a full on seizure (which I am not predisposed to). According to her, I was flopping around, spitting wildly and drooling all over my face, my eyes wide and glazed staring into nothing, lips turning blue. She immediately called 911 and within 5-10 minutes, two EMT's arrived and began to speak to me and take my vitals. For a good 15 minutes I couldn't sit up and had to lay on the ground, still extremely out of it - unable to think, merely in extreme discomfort similar to the most intense flu I've ever experienced. After a half hour or so, I sat up and was able to thank them for helping me and answer some of their questions. Over another 15 or so minutes they said all my vitals were perfect and they were not worried about me - sure I'd make a full recovery, which I hope I did. I am feeling MUCH better today. The reason I felt it so important to submit this report is because I had never heard of anyone experiencing side-effects that severe. Of course I had heard it could wipe you out, give you chills, aches, and exhaustion - but I had never heard that it could lead to a seizure so scary that my best friend thought I might be dying. I truly don't know what might have happened without her. People should know to have someone at home with them after the second dose. I am not over-exaggerating about my symptoms whatsoever. My body still hurts all over and I feel as if I went through some type of gauntlet yesterday. I absolutely do NOT want to discourage anyone from getting the vaccine, but I wish I had some notion that something so severe could happen to me.

After receiving my second COVID-19 vaccine, I began feeling feverish and achy about 20 hours after the shot. I left work early to come home and rest. About 34 hours after the shot, I woke up around 2:00 am with intense abdominal and back pain, a fever, and vomiting. I took Tylenol and tried to rest, but my discomfort continued throughout the day. By the afternoon of March 30, I began to worry that I was having more than a typical vaccine reaction. The PA who saw me assessed my symptoms, performed an abdominal exam, and then dismissed my issues as a bad vaccine reaction. He gave me an injection of toradol and sent me home. My symptoms subsided after the toradol injection, but I still felt unwell. On March 31, I had a previously scheduled visit with my primary care doctor. During the visit, I described my symptoms after receiving the vaccine, but I was told again that I was just having a really bad reaction to the vaccine. Throughout that day, my condition continued to worsen, and by the evening of the 31st I developed a fever and my abdominal pain returned. I scheduled an emergency telemedicine visit. I described my symptoms and described the pain I was feeling, but again, I was told I was having a bad vaccine reaction. On the morning of April 1, I woke up with a fever and debilitating abdominal pain. I drove myself to the ER where I was diagnosed appendicitis. My appendix was about to rupture, so I was rushed into surgery. I was released after several days but had to return.

37 2021-05-07 tremor Vaccine Adverse Event Report May 8th, 2021. Patient, had an appointment for his 2nd dose of Pfizer ... Read more
Close
Vaccine Adverse Event Report May 8th, 2021. Patient, had an appointment for his 2nd dose of Pfizer Covid 19 vaccine May 8th 2021 at 10:00am. His first dose of Pfizer Covid 19 was at our Pharmacy on April 16th, 2021. At around 10:15am, patient came in with his fiancé, who is a doctor at pediatric department, shown on her name tag. After processing the paperwork needed for vaccination, Pharmacist on duty, went over the VAR to ensure the provided information was adequate before it was ready for my intern to administer the shot. Patient looked fine as I was able to have a brief conversation with him while waiting for the shot. Due to some insurance issues that needed to be resolved, at 10:40am, pharmacy intern, took the patient to Patient Health Room for immunization. At 10:45am, I was ringing up a prescription at Terminal 42 when hearing the word, Help, coming from the Patient Health Room. Within seconds later, the door was opened as I was running out the pharmacy toward the Patient Health Room to see what happened. The patient was lying on the floor, unconscious, while his fiancé was calling his name asking whether he was okay and rolled him to his side and supported his head. I reached into the cabinet and prepared to administer an EPIPEN to the patient, meanwhile, pharmacy technicians, asked and dialed 911. As his fiancé kept calling his name, the patient gained consciousness. I asked intern what had happened to clarify whether it was a reaction due to the vaccination or not. Meanwhile, the patient's fiancé stated this event was not unexpected. Patient was able to talk and confirmed he was fine. Unfortunately, it appeared that the patient bruised his nose and forehead with slight blood from a minor cut. We instructed the patient and his fiancé to stay in the room and offered assistance upon request until EMS arrived. Patient's fiancé requested an ice pack for his bruise. Later on, the patient appeared to be shaking, so I asked the fiancé whether it was okay to give him some GATORADE. His fiancé also requested a glucose meter to check his blood sugar. The EMS arrived within minutes and patient was transported to hospital Before they were leaving, I asked the fiancé if there was anything she would like us to do as well as offered a follow-up. She declined the offer. I also asked briefly if she could share his medical condition, but the fiancé only disclosed that the patient has needle anxiety. The EMS also said that they will take it from here, and there is no additional action needed from our end at this time. Each team members who were involved in the event wrote reports and kept them filed in the pharmacy records.

At 1506, the client stated that he was feeling "weak and faint" and was transferred to the zero gravity reclining chair at that time. The client denied any medical history, stated he takes no medications, and has no allergies. The client stated he ate breakfast at 1000 and hadn't had anything to eat or drink since then. At 1509, the client's vital signs were as follows: blood pressure 100/60, heart rate 52, respiratory rate 20, O2 97%, temperature 96.3 (the client was still quite sweaty at the time.) The client's pulse was thready but regular. The client continued to appear diaphoretic but his color was improved. He was alert and oriented. The client stated that his symptoms had all resolved and he was feeling "back to normal." Education provided regarding v-safe, primary care follow up, symptom management, AMR activation and emergency management. At 1530, the client's vital signs were as follows: blood pressure 100/82, heart rate 72, pulse strong and regular, O2 96%. 37 2021-06-05 night sweats I received my second dose of the Pfizer / BioNTech COVID-19 vaccine on Tuesday, May 18, 2021 at 1:53... Read more
Close
I received my second dose of the Pfizer / BioNTech COVID-19 vaccine on Tuesday, May 18, 2021 at 1:53pm EDT. Many of the "typical" or "expected" side effects commenced about 12 hours later, including chills, night sweats, a slight fever (99.5), and headache and lethargy the following day. Nothing was particularly off-putting until the afternoon of Wednesday, May 19, 2021, when I noticed small red spots on my legs and feet. A Google search suggested petechiae and enough cause for me to go to a nearby urgent care clinic. The petechiae were present on both legs and feet (and eventually a few spots on my hands), though a little more pronounced on the left side (with one noteworthy cluster on my left leg). I had no apparent gum bleeding or bruising (maybe one bruise, but the urgent care doctor thought it was there beforehand). The doctor at the urgent care clinic confirmed petechiae and ran stat blood work for return that night. At ~9pm EDT on Wednesday, May 19, 2021, I received a phone call from the urgent care's centralized lab informing me that my platelet count was 2 (10^3/uL) -- dangerously low, with risk of spontaneous bleeding and in the worst case scenario brain hemorrhage -- and my PTT was 55.6 seconds. They told me to report to an emergency room immediately, the nearest of Medical Center. The diagnosis was eventually Immune Thrombocytopenia (ITP). Every physician I've encountered has felt that the occurrence one-day post-vaccination points to the vaccine as the cause. (For what it's worth, I do not think any of the doctors or nurses I encountered had never seen a platelet count so low. Most of them said as much.) My discharge papers officially note as the diagnoses: petechiae, thrombocytopenia, and adverse effect of vaccine. I have included details related to my platelet count, treatment course, and other figures below (and am happy to provide corroborating information where appropriate). The doctors did not run any d-dimers, PF4 HIT ELISA, or fibrinogen tests, and no imaging was performed, presumably because I did not present with any signs of simultaneous clotting (e.g., TTP or VITT). They've also told me that my haptoglobin and hemoglobin levels were normal (see below), which I am told helps support the notion that there was / is no clotting or "red blood cell breakdown." Search terms: decreased platelet count, immune thrombocytopenia, ITP, severely low platelet count, low platelets, petechiae, idiopathic thrombocytopenic purpura, immune thrombocytopenic purpura, vaccine-induced immune thrombocytopenia, vaccine-induced ITP

38 2021-06-02 tingling, burning sensation On day 2 or 3 of getting the shot, I started feeling a burning sensation in my chest and what felt l... Read more
Close
On day 2 or 3 of getting the shot, I started feeling a burning sensation in my chest and what felt like my heart. It was about 3 or 4 out of 10 on the pain scale. I also had intermittent tingling sensations, mostly on my cheek to the left of my nose, but also tingling in locations around my body which happened only a couple of times. My heart beat rapidly. It was similar to the heart palpitations I get when I eat certain foods. It also felt as if my heart was constrained, as if its outer layers were less flexible than usual. When the symptoms showed up I started following a fairly aggressive anti-inflammatory diet, mainly wheat/cereal and Advil. I spent most of the time lying in bed facing up, in order to minimize strain on my heart. I had trouble laying on my side, since my chest/heart was sensitive to pressure. I also believe I was more acutely aware of the distribution of blood throughout my body, and laying on my side felt similar to being upside down in that blood was pooling heavily at the bottom, but I may be misremembering the sensation. I don't know if I had shortness of breath, since I took care to avoid exertion. Since my heart was beating like crazy, exertion of any kind seemed like a really bad idea. The symptoms did not change in severity for a couple days. On day 4 or 5 of getting the shot, I felt slightly feverish for about a 10 minute period. During this time, I noticed the burning sensation weakening slightly, and I began feeling a soreness on my chest near my left shoulder, which I believe is a lymph node area. Each day after, the symptoms and my heart calmed down little by little. ---- On day 9, I went to the emergency room since I still had heart palpitations and the burning sensation at about a 1/10 pain level. Just sitting upright caused my heart to go into overdrive. The hospital did not find anything out of the ordinary. I was given MAALOX, but the burning sensation was too faint to know if there was any improvement as a result. Their best theory is that I had costochondritis. ---- On day 11, after eating dinner I started getting "chronic hiccups". These last anywhere from 10 minutes to a couple of hours without stopping. I am not sure whether food or drinks cause them. They are short/acute hiccups and happen at an interval of about 10-15 seconds. I have no history of such a thing. ---- Today is day 12. The symptoms are noticeably better since I visited the hospital, but the burning sensation is still present around what feels like my heart and the hiccups aren't stopping. My best theory is that I may have had an infection by the time I got the vaccine. Maybe I had an infection, not necessarily COVID but some related virus, that was kept in check below an immune response threshold until the vaccine came along and led to the immune system burning the whole infection down.
